<paragraph blockId="40.[151,1436,1948,2009]" lastBlockId="41.[151,1436,151,464]" lastPageId="41" lastPageNumber="42" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">
In the studied sample, there are also numerous double triaenes with short rhabds bearing two opposed cladomes that are called amphitriaenes (
<figureCitation box="[510,606,1984,2009]" captionStart="FIGURE 25" captionStartId="41.[151,250,1278,1300]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,519,1256]" captionTargetId="figure@41.[151,1437,519,1256]" captionTargetPageId="41" captionText="FIGURE 25. Spicules of sponges of the order Spirophorida; A – H—Amphitriaenes of Samus anonymus, family Samidae." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/287810/files/figure.png" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">
Figs. 
<number box="[578,606,1984,2009]" pageId="40" pageNumber="41" value="25.0">25</number>
</figureCitation>
A–H). The investigated amphitriaenes exceed 
<number box="[1154,1196,1985,2009]" pageId="40" pageNumber="41" value="330.0">330</number>
µm in size and are identical to those of the Recent cosmopolitan samid species 
<taxonomicName authority="Gray, 1867" authorityName="Gray" authorityYear="1867" box="[826,1178,151,176]" class="Demospongiae" family="Samidae" genus="Samus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Spirophorida" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="anonymous">
<emphasis box="[826,1034,152,176]" italics="true" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Samus anonymous</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Gray" box="[1041,1178,151,176]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" refString="Gray, J. E. (1867 a) Notes on the Arrangement of Sponges, with the Descriptions of some New Genera. Proceedings of the Zoological Society of London, 1867 (2), 492 - 558." type="journal article" year="1867" yearSuffix="a">
Gray, 
<number box="[1109,1165,151,176]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" value="1867.0">1867</number>
a
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[1193,1287,151,176]" captionStart="FIGURE 26" captionStartId="42.[151,250,1913,1935]" captionTargetBox="[180,1411,409,1890]" captionTargetId="figure@42.[180,1412,409,1893]" captionTargetPageId="42" captionText="FIGURE 26. Spicules of recent sponges; A—Spicules of Chondrilla nucula (from Rützler et al. 2007); B—Spicules of Chondrilla secunda (from Fromont et al. 2008); C, D—Amphiclads of Samus anonymus (from van Soest &amp; Hooper 2002 a)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/287811/files/figure.png" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">
Figs. 
<number box="[1257,1287,151,176]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" value="26.0">26</number>
</figureCitation>
C, D). Today, sponges of this monotypic genus are reported from shallow depths, caves and are excavating limestone substrates in many parts of the world as the coasts of 
<collectingCountry box="[630,698,223,248]" name="Brazil" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Brazil</collectingCountry>
and East Africa, the Adriatic and Aegean Sea, and Mediterranean (van 
<bibRefCitation author="Soest" box="[215,429,260,285]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" refString="Soest, R. W. M., van, Boury-Esnault, N., Hooper, J. N. A., Rutzler, K., de Voogd, N. J., Alvarez de Glasby, B., Hajdu, E., Pisera, A. B., Manconi, R., Schoenberg, C., Janussen, D., Tabachnick, K. R., Klautau, M., Picton, B., Kelly, M., Vacelet, J., Dohrmann, M. &amp; Cristina Diaz, M. (2013) World Porifera database. Accessed through: Van Soest, R. W. M., Boury- Esnault, N., Hooper, J. N. A., Rutzler, K., de Voogd, N. J., Alvarez de Glasby, B., Hajdu, E., Pisera, A. B., Manconi, R., Schoenberg, C., Janussen, D., Tabachnick, K. R., Klautau, M., Picton, B., Kelly, M., Vacelet, J., Dohrmann, M. &amp; Cristina Diaz, M. World Porifera database. Available from: http: // www. marinespecies. org / porifera / porifera. php? p = taxdetails &amp; id = 171271 (accessed 19 March 2014)" type="journal article" year="2013">
Soest 
<emphasis box="[290,346,260,285]" italics="true" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">et al</emphasis>
. 
<number box="[368,429,260,284]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" value="2013.0">2013</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). This genus is reported from 
<collectingCountry box="[808,911,260,285]" name="Australia" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Australia</collectingCountry>
e.g., by 
<bibRefCitation author="Gray" box="[1029,1189,260,285]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" refString="Gray, J. E. (1867 a) Notes on the Arrangement of Sponges, with the Descriptions of some New Genera. Proceedings of the Zoological Society of London, 1867 (2), 492 - 558." type="journal article" year="1867" yearSuffix="a">
Gray (
<number box="[1108,1168,260,285]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" value="1867.0">1867</number>
a)
</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Carter" box="[1208,1381,260,285]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" refString="Carter, H. J. (1879 b) Contributions to our Knowledge of the Spongida. Annals and Magazine of Natural History, Series 5, 3 (17), 284 - 304, 343 - 360. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1080 / 00222937908694101" type="journal article" year="1879" yearSuffix="b">
Carter (
<number box="[1301,1359,260,285]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" value="1879.0">1879</number>
b)
</bibRefCitation>
and Wiedenmayer (
<number box="[322,381,296,320]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" value="1994.0">1994</number>
) and allows me to assign the studied fossil spicules to 
<emphasis box="[993,1208,296,320]" italics="true" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">
<taxonomicName box="[993,1204,296,320]" class="Demospongiae" family="Samidae" genus="Samus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Spirophorida" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="anonymous">Samus anonymous</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="41.[151,1436,151,464]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">
Samids have a rather sparse fossil record. So far, they have been described from the Miocene of 
<collectingCountry box="[1341,1436,332,357]" name="Portugal" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Portugal</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Pisera" box="[158,365,367,392]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" refString="Pisera, A., Cachao, M. &amp; da Silva, C. (2006) Siliceous sponge spicules from the Miocene Mem Moniz marls (Portugal) and their environmental significance. Rivista Italiana de Paleontologia, 112, 287 - 299." type="journal article" year="2006">
Pisera 
<emphasis box="[238,289,367,392]" italics="true" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">et al</emphasis>
. 
<number box="[307,365,367,392]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" value="2006.0">2006</number>
</bibRefCitation>
) and from the Eocene and the Holocene sediments (Wiedenmayer 
<number box="[1141,1200,368,392]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" value="1994.0">1994</number>
, after 
<bibRefCitation author="Pulitzer-Finali" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" refString="Pulitzer-Finali, G. (1983) A collection of Mediterranean Demospongiae (Porifera) with, in appendix, a list of the Demospongiae hitherto recorded from the Mediterranean Sea. Annali del Museo civico di storia naturale &quot; Giacomo Doria &quot;, 84, 445 - 621." type="journal article" year="1983">
Pulitzer-Finali 
<number box="[151,210,404,428]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" value="1983.0">1983</number>
</bibRefCitation>
), and recently from the late Early Miocene deposits of the Slovakian part of the Vienna Basin, Central Paratethys (
<bibRefCitation author="Lukowiak" box="[282,526,439,464]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" refString="Lukowiak, M., Pisera, A. &amp; Schlogl, J. (2014) Bathyal sponges from the late Early Miocene of the Vienna Basin (central Paratethys, Slovakia). Palaontologische Zeitschrift, 88 (3), 263 - 277. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1007 / s 12542 - 013 - 0197 - x" type="journal article" year="2014">
Łukowiak 
<emphasis box="[404,453,439,464]" italics="true" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">et al</emphasis>
. 
<number box="[467,526,440,464]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" value="2014.0">2014</number>
</bibRefCitation>
, figs. 
<number box="[593,606,439,464]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" value="5.0">5</number>
A–D).
</paragraph>
